The thirteenth season of _[Criminal Minds](/wiki/Criminal_Minds "Criminal
Minds")_ was ordered on April 7, 2017, by CBS with an order of 22
episodes.[1][2] The season premiered on September 27, 2017 in a new time slot
at 10:00PM on Wednesday when it had previously been at 9:00PM on Wednesday
since its inception. The season concluded on April 18, 2018 with a two-part
season finale.[3]

"Edit section: Cast")]

The entire main cast from the previous season returned for the season, except
[Damon Gupton](/wiki/Damon_Gupton "Damon Gupton") (Stephen Walker), who was
fired from the show.[4][5] His character was killed off in the season premiere
off-screen.

Following the cancellation of _[Criminal Minds: Beyond

###
Development[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Criminal_Minds_\(season_13\)&action=edit&section=7
"Edit section: Development")]

_Criminal Minds_ was renewed for a thirteenth season with an episode order of
22 episodes on April 7, 2017.[1][2] The entire main cast from the previous
season returned for the season, except [Damon Gupton](/wiki/Damon_Gupton
"Damon Gupton") (Stephen Walker), who was fired from the show.[4][5]

[Matthew Gray Gubler](/wiki/Matthew_Gray_Gubler "Matthew Gray Gubler")
directed the seventeenth episode of the season and it was said to be "the
spookiest episode of Season 13" and involved clowns.[7] On August 10, 2017, it
was revealed that [Aisha Tyler](/wiki/Aisha_Tyler "Aisha Tyler") will make her
television directing debut and direct the sixth episode of the season.[8] On
August 12, 2017 it was revealed that [Erica Messer](/wiki/Erica_Messer "Erica
Messer") and [Kirsten Vangsness](/wiki/Kirsten_Vangsness "Kirsten Vangsness")
will be co-writing the eleventh episode of the season, which will be the
fourth episode they have co-written together.[9] On October 31, 2017, it was
announced that [Adam Rodriguez](/wiki/Adam_Rodriguez "Adam Rodriguez") will
make his Criminal Minds directing debut and direct the sixteenth episode of
the season.[10]

###
Casting[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Criminal_Minds_\(season_13\)&action=edit&section=8
"Edit section: Casting")]

[![](//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5b/Shemar_Moore_Cannes_2012.jpg/130px-
Shemar_Moore_Cannes_2012.jpg)](/wiki/File:Shemar_Moore_Cannes_2012.jpg)

[](/wiki/File:Shemar_Moore_Cannes_2012.jpg "Enlarge")

[Shemar Moore](/wiki/Shemar_Moore "Shemar Moore") reprised his role as [Derek
Morgan](/wiki/Derek_Morgan_\(Criminal_Minds\) "Derek Morgan \(Criminal
Minds\)") in the fifth episode.

On June 11, 2017, it was announced that Damon Gupton had been let go from the
show after one season.[4] CBS said his departure was "part of a creative
change on the show".[4][5] His character Stephen Walker was killed off-screen
in the season premiere.

On June 20, 2017, CBS announced that [Daniel Henney](/wiki/Daniel_Henney
"Daniel Henney"), who was a series regular on _[Criminal Minds: Beyond
Borders](/wiki/Criminal_Minds:_Beyond_Borders "Criminal Minds: Beyond
Borders")_ as [Matt Simmons](/wiki/Matt_Simmons_\(Criminal_Minds\) "Matt
Simmons \(Criminal Minds\)"), would join the main show as a series regular for
the thirteenth season.[11]

On October 12, 2017, it was announced that [Shemar Moore](/wiki/Shemar_Moore
"Shemar Moore") would reprise his role as [Derek
Morgan](/wiki/Derek_Morgan_\(Criminal_Minds\) "Derek Morgan \(Criminal
Minds\)") in the fifth episode of the season ("Lucky Strikes"). His character
returned to help Penelope Garcia get through a tough time.[12]
